Results

Total community abundances ranged ~3 order of magnitude from 1.1e+04 to 6.4e+06 with average community abundance of 7.8e+05 \(\pm\) 9.9e+05 individuals m-2. Community mean body sizes exhibited a similar range from 1.1e-01 to 1.4e+02 with an average community mean body size of 3.34 \(\pm\) 12.71 mg dry mass individual-1.

The cross community relationship between community mean body size and total community abundance exhibited little evidence of a clear relationship between these variables aross NEON streams (Figure 1). The median slope estimate between \(log_{10} \overline{M^{0.75}}\) and \(log_{10} N_{total}\) was 0.01 (-0.17–0.18; 95% credible interval). Within-site slope estimates ranged from -0.1 \(\pm\) -0.5 – 0.14 to 0.09 \(\pm\) -0.12 – 0.5 (Figure 1 inset).

Appendix

Body size treatment

While the calculation of total abundance is straightforward, estimating mean body size of the community can be done in multiple ways: 1) by taking the mean of all individuals (i.e., abundance-weighted mean), by calculating the relative biomass of each body size and using this to weight body size by relative biomass (i.e., biomass-weighted), and lastly to correct each mass to metabolic mass (M0.75) and take the abundance- or biomass-weighted mean of these corrected body sizes. The theorized relationship between abundance and body size in \(N \propto M\) is based on energy use, i.e. metabolism, and metabolism scales non-linearly with body size, therefore, the metabolic correction is most appropriate (white2007?). These differences can have significant influence on the community biomass estimates (Figure S1).

While the calculation of total abundance is straightforward, estimating mean body size of the community can be done in multiple ways: 1) by taking the mean of all individuals (i.e., abundance-weighted mean) or by calculating the relative biomass of each body size and using this to weight body size by relative biomass (i.e., biomass-weighted). The theorized relationship between abundance and body size in is based on energy use, i.e. metabolism, and metabolism scales non-linearly with body size, biomass weighting is the most appropriate choice. Below

Further, the theories of self-thinning and energy equivalence upon which the CCSR is based upon derive from individual energy use, which body size is only a proxy for. We can adjust body mass, sensu stricto, to metabolic mass by adjusting for the metabolic scaling exponent, \(M^{\alpha}\), where \(\alpha\) usually takes values in the range of 0.6 – 0.75. Also, care must be taken about how metabolic mass is calculated. Because, individual metabolism is a non-linear function with mass, \(f(\overline{x}) \neq \overline{f(x)}\) {Jensen 1979} and the proper value to use is to first calculate metabolic mass for each individual, \(m^{\alpha}_{i}\), and then average across all individual metabolic mass measurements for a sampling timepoint. The difference in these measurements can be observed below.
